<h2 id="what-is-anomaly">Overview</h2>

<p>In this tutorial you will learn how to access a report with your latest anomalous transactions, how to see all your transactions patterns and anomalies in a nice chart, how to receive notifications via email or webhooks when something anomalous happens and how to change your settings.</p>

<p>Let's get started!</p>

<h2 id="interface">Interface presentation</h2>

<p>You can access all information for your patterns via CloudWalk Manager, at <a href='http://manager.cloudwalk.io/transactions/patterns' class='external'>manager.cloudwalk.io/transactions/patterns</a>.</p>

<p class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">You won't see anything at Manager unless you have done at least one transaction using your CloudWalk account.</p>

<p>This is the first screen you'll see:</p>

<span class="todo">Insert manager.cloudwalk.io/transactions/patterns screenshot</span>

<p>In the next two sections we explain what you'll find accessing the anomalies tab (1) and the notifications settings (2). The Patterns tab is so awesome it will be the focus of the second part of this tutorial.</p>

<h2 id="anomalies-report">Anomalies report</h2>

<p>This is the default tab you arrive when you access the transactions patterns URL. As you can see in the above image, we highlight the time when we detected the last anomaly (3).</p>

<p> Down the screen (4) you can see a table with the 10 last anomalies detected. You can expand each line of the table to see more details about the corresponding transaction.</p>

<h2 id="setting-notifications">Setting notifications</h2>

<p>This is a view from the notifications panel:</p>

<span class="todo">Insert manager.cloudwalk.io/transactions/patterns?tab=3 (settings) screenshot</span>

<p>Here you can set an e-mail that will receive notifications when a new anomaly is found.</p>

<p>There is also an option to configure a webhook that will receive HTTP Posts of new anomalies. The payload will be a JSON with structure similar to this example:</p>

<pre><code data-language="javascript">{
    "notification_type": "anomaly",
    "sent_at": "2014-09-17T21:35:17.136707",
    "description": {
        "url": "http://http-echo.cloudwalk.io",
        "count": 359098,
        "model_params": {
            "min_pts": 40,
            "eps": 20
        },
        "request": {
            "buffer": "\"012345678\"",
            "timestamp": "2014-09-17T21:35:02",
            "size": "9"
        },
        "response": {
            "buffer": "\"CLOUDWALK 012345678\" ",
            "timestamp": "2014-09-17T21:35:02",
            "size": "19"
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>

